abstract: Although Democrats and Republicans agreed that the law had led to overly punitive stakes, Congress had been unable to come to an accord on replacing it.
snippet: Although Democrats and Republicans agreed that the law had led to overly punitive stakes, Congress had been unable to come to an accord on replacing it.
lead_paragraph: Overcoming years of partisan bickering over the federal government’s role in public education, congressional negotiators came to an agreement on Thursday to revise the No Child Left Behind law for the first time since it was signed by President George W. Bush 14 years ago.

abstract: A bill would allow a type of tax-exempt bond that helped cut sulfur dioxide pollution decades ago to be used for carbon capture and storage projects.
snippet: A bill would allow a type of tax-exempt bond that helped cut sulfur dioxide pollution decades ago to be used for carbon capture and storage projects.
lead_paragraph: For years, power companies, manufacturers and entrepreneurs have tried to make capturing and storing carbon emissions from industrial operations like burning coal into a business, to little avail.

abstract: Turner Classic Movies salutes Southern writers with “In Cold Blood.” Philip Seymour Hoffman channels Truman Capote. And “Empire” declares war.
snippet: Turner Classic Movies salutes Southern writers with “In Cold Blood.” Philip Seymour Hoffman channels Truman Capote. And “Empire” declares war.
lead_paragraph: Lock the doors before watching “In Cold Blood,” part of the Turner Classic Movies spotlight on Southern writers. Then double the chill with Philip Seymour Hoffman’s tour de force in “Capote.” Meanwhile, “Empire” declares a war of words.

abstract: BlazerCon was a place for soccer fans to mingle, but also a kind of informal trade show for international leagues and club executives to pitch themselves to the sport’s growing American fan base.
snippet: BlazerCon was a place for soccer fans to mingle, but also a kind of informal trade show for international leagues and club executives to pitch themselves to the sport’s growing American fan base.
lead_paragraph: “I feel like I just wandered into the soccer-themed bar mitzvah I never had,” said Roger Bennett, one-half of the Men in Blazers duo, seconds after bounding up onto the stage Friday evening to open the festivities at the first BlazerCon, a Comic-Con for soccer nerds.

abstract: Research into veterans’ suicide received a lift on Tuesday with Senate passage of a measure requiring an independent research program on the effects of combat service on suicide rates and other mental health issues among troops and veterans.
snippet: Research into veterans’ suicide received a lift on Tuesday with Senate passage of a measure requiring an independent research program on the effects of combat service on suicide rates and other mental health issues among troops and veterans.
lead_paragraph: Research into veterans’ suicide received a lift on Tuesday with Senate passage of a measure requiring an independent research program on the effects of combat service on suicide rates and other mental health issues among troops and veterans. A report by The New York Times in September found that monitoring of suicide was not coordinated between the Department of Veterans Affairs and Department of Defense, and many veterans fell through the cracks because the effect of combat exposure was poorly tracked.   After more than decade of war, neither department has the data to show whether troops exposed to combat have a higher risk of suicide, and how that risk changes over time. Because of this, veterans say suicide prevention programs do not fit their needs. “We simply don’t know enough about the effects of combat on mental health issues among service members and veterans both during and after service,” said the amendment’s sponsor, Senator Michael Bennet of Colorado. The measure passed as part of the Military Construction and Veterans Affairs and Related Agencies Appropriations Act for fiscal year 2016.

lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A routine trip to run errands almost cost Katherine Dean her life. In February, just as Ms. Dean, of suburban Maryland, drove underneath a bridge on the Capital Beltway, a large chunk of concrete fell from the structure, crushing the hood of her car and smashing the windshield.

abstract: Thom Browne, Francisco Costa and more pick works for an auction sponsored by the CFDA.
snippet: Thom Browne, Francisco Costa and more pick works for an auction sponsored by the CFDA.
lead_paragraph: Art and fashion are famously symbiotic — but a new auction shows just how much designers have drawn influences from works of art. For a new sale on the site Paddle8, 20 American designers — including Michael Kors, Thom Browne, Francisco Costa and Diane von Furstenberg — have each picked one piece of art that has influenced their work; the proceeds of the sale will go to benefit the CFDA and its programs. (The Alice + Olivia designer Stacey Bendet Eisner has even donated a Francesco Clemente painting.) Click through the slide show here to see the work that inspires each designer — and why.

abstract: When the radio host speaks for angry Republicans in Iowa — and beyond — the 2016 candidates have no choice but to listen.
snippet: When the radio host speaks for angry Republicans in Iowa — and beyond — the 2016 candidates have no choice but to listen.
lead_paragraph: Talk of alpha and beta males is common in the suburban Des Moines studio of the nationally syndicated conservative talk-show host Steve Deace. Almost daily, he assails the wimpy betas purporting to rule today’s Republican Party — the feckless politicians who, under siege, are giving ground to alpha fighters like him. Such chatter includes references to ‘‘manginas’’ and ‘‘growing a pair,’’ yet does not seem to put off the women in Deace’s audience; after all, being politically incorrect has become a conservative badge of honor in 2015.
